  <section id="about" class="py-5" style="background-color: #D4EAD0;">
    <div class="container">
      <h2 class="text-center mb-4">About Cebu</h2>
      <p class="lead text-center">
        Cebu, also known as the “Queen City of the South,” is one of the most developed provinces in the Philippines. It
        is rich in history, culture, and natural beauty. Cebu is famous for its stunning beaches, world-class diving
        spots, historical landmarks like Magellan’s Cross, and the vibrant Sinulog Festival. Whether you're an
        adventurer, a foodie, or a history enthusiast, Cebu has something to offer everyone.

        Cebu is the largest island in the Visayas region and holds a significant place in Spanish colonial history. It
        was the original capital of the Philippines until the 17th century. Today, Cebu is home to six major cities:
        Cebu City, Danao, Lapu-Lapu, Mandaue, Toledo, and Talisay.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section id="highlight" class="py-5" style="background-color: #E9F4E7;">
    <div class="container">
      <h2 class="text-center mb-4">What Cebu is Known For</h2>
      <p class="lead text-center">
        Cebu is not just about beautiful islands, but also about its rich culture and vibrant traditions. It is famous
        for its delicious local cuisine, such as lechon (roast pig), dried mangoes, and the famous "sutukil" (a Cebuano
        style of cooking seafood). The island also boasts its historical significance, being the site of the first
        Spanish settlement in the Philippines.
      </p>
      <div class="row">
        <div class="col-md-4 mt-5">
          <h5 class="text-center">Food</h5>
          <p class="text-center">Cebu is known for its delectable dishes like lechon, which is a must-try for every
            visitor. Don't forget to try local snacks like otap, dried mangoes, and the sweet cinnamon bun called
            "bibingka."</p>
        </div>
        <div class="col-md-4 mt-5">
          <h5 class="text-center">Traditions</h5>
          <p class="text-center">The Sinulog Festival, celebrated every January, is one of the grandest festivals in the
            country. It features street dancing, religious processions, and colorful costumes that highlight Cebu's deep
            cultural and religious roots.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="col-md-4 mt-5">
          <h5 class="text-center">History</h5>
          <p class="text-center">Cebu is home to historical landmarks such as Magellan’s Cross, the Basilica Minore del
            Santo Niño, and Fort San Pedro, which remind visitors of the city’s rich colonial past.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

